Cassia fistula is widely grown as an ornamental plant in tropical and subtropical areas. It blooms in late spring. Flowering is profuse, with trees being covered with yellow flowers, many times with almost no leaf being seen. It will grow well in dry climates. Growth for this tree is best in full sun on well-drained soil; it is relatively drought tolerant and slightly salt-tolerant. It will tolerate light brief frost but can get damaged if frost persists. It can be subject to mildew, leaf spot especially during the second half of the growing season. The tree will bloom better where there is pronounced difference between summer and winter temperatures.

Neem is a fast-growing tree that can reach a height of 15-20m,rarely to 35-40 m. It is evergreen,but in severe drought it may shed most or nearly all of its leaves. The branches are wide spread. The fairly dense crown is roundish or oval and may reach the diameter of 15-20 m in old, free-standing specimens.

A baniyan is a tree that starts its life as an epiphyte when its seeds germinate in the cracks and crevices on a host tree."Banyan" often refers specifically to the indian banyan,the national tree of india, though the term has been generalized to include all figs that share a unique life cycle,and systematically to  refer to the subgenus urostigma. The seeds of banyans are dispersed by fruit-eating birds. The seeds germinate and send down roots towards the ground,and may envelop part of the host tree or building structure with roots , giving them the casual name of strangler fig. The strangling growth habit is found in a number of tropical forest species, particularly of the genius ficus, that compete for light.

The Golden Shower Tree (Cassia fistula) is a flowering plant.It blooms in April May.In Ayurvedic medicine, Golden Shower Tree is known as aragvadha ("disease killer").The golden shower tree is the state flower of Kerala in India.The flowers are of ritual importance in the Vishu festival of Kerala state of India.

The jackfruit is a species of tree in the mulberry family, which is native to parts of Southern and Southeast Asia. It is the national fruit of Bangladesh. Jackfruit is also found in East Africa e.g. in Uganda, as well as Northeastern Brazil.

It is well suited to tropical lowlands. Its fruit is the largest tree-borne fruit in the world reaching 80 pounds (36 kg) in weight and up to 36 inches (90 cm) long and 20 inches (50 cm) in diameter.[3]

Golden Shower Tree â€“known in the Malayalam language as Kanikkonna or Konna â€“ is a flowering plant of the Fabaceae species common in all South Asian countries. The scientific name is Cassia fistula and is also known as the Indian Laburnum in some places. The Kanikkonna is significant in the life of the Keralites and is inseparably connected to their culture. This is the state flower, and is a ritual item in the festivities connected with the Vishu festival. The medium-sized tree blooms in a particular season during the Medam month of Malayalam calendar (April-May), when Keralites celebrate Vishu.

A tree that is about 16 years old, and has been flowering for the past many years.  Was watered regularly till it became a full grown tree.
The tree is just outside the house gate, very near the main road.  The branches are occasionally trimmed by people from the electricity board, so that the branches don't get caught in the wires.

About 2 years back a large truck hit one of the two branches coming out of the first main fork of the tree. The branch tore away from the tree the following morning. But no weakness has been observed in the tree.

This tree was regularly lopped at the first fork as it used to get entangled in the electric wires and hence never grew properly. About 8-9 years ago one branch of the tree grew such that it averted the wires and that branch grew tall and regularly flowers since then. Now no branches ever sprout below the wires and hence no lopping happens.
